            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei-Lin Tan is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fog and its relentless innovation. Born in the Sunset District to Taiwanese immigrants who ran a small neighborhood grocery store, her childhood was a study in pragmatism and tireless work. Her parents, who spoke of stability above all else, hoped she would become a doctor or an accountant. However, Mei-Lin was always dismantling things\u2014radios, clocks, toasters\u2014less out of mischief and more from a deep-seated need to understand how they worked and how they could be better.\n\nHer choice to attend the California College of the Arts for Industrial Design was a quiet rebellion. It was a path her parents couldn\u2019t comprehend, but one she knew was her own. She graduated in the mid-90s, just as the first dot-com boom was igniting Silicon Valley. Her career began with designing clunky, beige computer peripherals and early PDAs, a tangible history of the tech world's awkward adolescence. She survived the dot-com bust, a key turning point that taught her resilience and the value of designing products with real, lasting utility.\n\nNow 50 and divorced, Mei-Lin is the Director of Hardware Product Design for a manufacturing firm in the Dogpatch. She lives in a tastefully renovated Edwardian in Glen Park with her 16-year-old son, Leo. Her 6.1-mile drive to the office is a cherished ritual, a mental bridge between the domestic quiet of her neighborhood and the high-stakes world of global supply chains and product launches. Her days are a blur of team meetings, calls with factories in Shenzhen, and refining the ergonomics of the next must-have device.\n\nSocially, her circle is small and tight-knit, consisting of old colleagues who weathered the same industry storms. They meet for dinners in Hayes Valley, reminiscing and debating the future of design. Having achieved financial success, Mei-Lin\u2019s aspirations have shifted. She dreams of stepping away from the corporate ladder to start a small consultancy focused on mentoring young, diverse designers. She envisions a future where she can pour her decades of experience not just into polished consumer goods, but into the people who will shape the world next."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was nine, sitting on the dusty floor in the back of her parents\u2019 grocery store. The guts of a broken toaster were spread across the concrete like a surgical diagram. She wasn't breaking it; she was understanding it. When her father found her, he just sighed, his expression a mix of confusion and weary disappointment. In that moment, holding a small heating coil, Mei-Lin felt a quiet, firm certainty. This was a language she understood, even if no one else in her world did. This curiosity became her compass.\n\n2.\nThe acceptance letter from CCA wasn\u2019t just thick paper; it was a tectonic shift. It arrived on a foggy Tuesday when she was 18. She held it in her bedroom, the words blurring as a wave of terror and exhilarating freedom washed over her. Telling her parents felt like a confession, their silence confirming it was a path she would walk alone. The memory isn\u2019t of a fight, but of a quiet, internal declaration of independence. It was the first thing she ever designed: her own future.\n\n3.\nIt was the silence that struck her most. The SOMA loft, once buzzing with the frantic energy of the dot-com boom, was now an echo chamber of abandoned desks and useless Aeron chairs. 2001. At 28, she stood by her empty station, the last one to leave. The failure wasn\u2019t just financial; it was philosophical. The market for flimsy, flashy gadgets had evaporated. It was then she vowed to only design things with weight, purpose, and lasting utility. That day, resilience was forged from the wreckage of ambition.\n\n4.\nLeo was eight, and he had spent the entire afternoon building an impossibly complex LEGO starship on the living room floor. He explained its warp drive and escape pods with the same intense focus she once gave to toasters. As she listened, a profound sense of recognition bloomed in her chest, so powerful it almost hurt. She saw her own relentless need to build and improve reflected in him, but purer, joyful. It was a legacy more tangible and important than any product she could ever ship.\n\n5.\nJust last winter, driving over the 280 interchange towards Dogpatch, the city lights below looked like a scattered circuit board. A young designer on her team was struggling, and Mei-Lin had spent an hour talking her through a crisis of confidence. In a flash of clarity on that bridge, she realized her pride wasn't in the finished product anymore, but in the moment the designer\u2019s voice had steadied. The ambition to climb ladders fell away, replaced by the quiet, powerful desire to build people up instead."
